Hinshaw 1
-
-
- Rebecca Hinshaw
-
- Mrs. Siar
-
- English IV
-
- October 25, 2011
-
-
- The Man Of Law
-
- “A sergeant of law… Discreet he was and of great reverence; At least he seemed so, his words were so wise” (Chaucer). In the Canterbury tales, Chaucer’s pilgrim, the man of law, is devoted and hardworking much like Elle Woods from ‘Legally Blonde’ because she too was completely indulged in her practice as a lawyer.
-
- The Canterbury tales, set in the medieval period, are a collection of stories told by 27 different pilgrims as they are on their way to the shrine of the martyr Saint Thomas Becket in Canterbury.
-
- As Described by Chaucer, the man of law was dressed in a coat belted by a silk sash (Chaucer). Unfortunately, his physical appearance is not described much throughout his prologue and tale, however one could imagine his aged face, adorned with wrinkles of wisdom.
-
- He was a devoted student of the laws of the land, highly respected and held with great reverence amongst his peers. As a member of the court, his job entails representing his clients in the courtroom. In addition, lawyers draw up legal documents
-
- Hinshaw 2
-
and handle out-of-court settlements. They spend much of their time preparing arguments and researching precedents. (CITE).
-
- The man of law seems to be argumentative because after his tale, the parson, another pilgrim, argues with him because of his swearing. The man of law seems to highly respect Chaucer because before he begins his story, he apologizes and says that he couldn’t possibly tell a story that Chaucer hasn’t already told (CITE). “In the Prologue to his tale, the Man of Law laments the miseries of poverty. He then remarks how fortunate merchants are, and says that his tale is one told to him by a merchant.” (CITE)
